I think they are great for the purpose they serve.
@mixedbyel X #GregGotTheShot

A "run and gun" music video is a style of music video production that involves capturing footage quickly and spontaneously without a detailed plan or pre-production. The term "run and gun" refers to the fast-paced, on-the-go nature of the filming process, where the director and crew may have to quickly set up shots and capture footage in various locations without much time for preparation.

This style of music video is often associated with a DIY aesthetic and a gritty, unpolished look. The video may feature handheld camera work, natural lighting, and a focus on capturing authentic moments rather than staged scenes. The style is often used for music videos that have a low budget or a short turnaround time.

Overall, a "run and gun" music video is characterized by its fast-paced, spontaneous nature and its focus on capturing authentic moments on the fly.

How I edit my Run N Gun Music Videos…
1) Add the music track to my timeline
2) Manually sync all performance takes to the music track
3) Work on my color grade, because I hate watching LOG footage 🤢
4) Vibe out and make all of my cuts to the beat
5) Break down the takes into what I want to use for the verses and hooks
6) Add in any BRoll where I see fit
7) Go through the edit over and over, refining my cuts and edits

That’s my simple Run N Gun edit process! 👌🏽
So much more goes into editing more elaborate projects.
#GregGotTheShot

I got into flying FPV, because I had very specific ideas for shots that are just not possible with normal camera drones. I quickly realized that the shots I had in mind do not come easily and require lots of practice. 

I’m finally getting to the point where i’d be confident that I can capture the look I had in mind before I started. 

Sticking to your path is crucial as it ensures consistency, growth, and achievement. It helps you navigate challenges, maintain focus, and ultimately reach your goals. By staying committed, you build resilience and make steady progress toward your desired outcomes.

People are seeing me post my FPV videos and they think it’s cool. I don’t think many people realize that it’s nothing like operating a normal camera drone 🤦🏽‍♂️ it requires much more practice and focus. Flying around doing nothing is a lot easier than attempting plan out a specific and capturing it with multiple other elements like moving actors, cars or whatever else…

I’m a lot better than I was when I started, but I’m also very far from what I’d like to be doing with it. I’m getting there though 👌🏽
#GregGotTheShot

Since the beginning of me offering video services, for the most part, I’ve tried to avoid including any serious audio recording. Recording and mixing high quality audio is beyond me. It’s just something that I didn’t really care to invest tons of time into learning. So, up until now, it’s continued to be a weakness of mine.

I don’t remember what @mixedbyel and I were talking about at the start of the conversation, but it turned into much needed lesson for me, about how to clean up audio for the interviews and documentary work that I am planning to get into soon! I’m usually able to sit and get what I need from a few YouTube videos, but having someone close to me with knowledge in that field with the ability to provide instant feedback was far more helpful than trying to figure it out on my own. 

========================================

Having people around that you can learn from is crucial for gaining new knowledge, honing skills, broadening perspectives, and fostering personal growth. It creates a supportive and enriching environment that empowers you to become a more well-rounded and accomplished individual.

Cover art plays a pivotal role in the music industry, and it’s particularly significant for rap artists. Here’s why it matters:

First Impressions Count: Your cover art is the first thing listeners see. It’s the handshake that introduces your music, making it crucial for leaving a lasting impression.

Visual Storytelling: Similar to your lyrics, cover art tells a story. It sets the tone, conveying what your music is about and sparking curiosity.

Branding: Think of it as your musical logo. Consistent and memorable cover art builds recognition and fosters a sense of trust among your audience.

Social Media Impact: In today’s digital age, shareable and visually captivating cover art can generate buzz on social media platforms, expanding your reach.

Setting the Mood: Your cover art provides a glimpse into the mood and style of your music. It’s a sneak peek that entices potential listeners.

Unique Identity: In a crowded industry, distinctive cover art helps you stand out. It becomes an integral part of your artistic identity.

Collector’s Appeal: Physical copies of music with compelling cover art become collectibles, connecting fans more deeply with your work.

Album Definition: Your album’s cover art defines the project, encapsulating its essence and serving as a symbol of the music within.

Building Anticipation: A teaser of your cover art can create excitement and anticipation for your release, akin to a movie trailer before the main event.

Honoring Creativity: Cover art is a canvas for artistic expression. It showcases your creativity as an artist beyond just your music.

In the world of music, every detail contributes to your overall message. So, don’t underestimate the significance of your cover art. It’s your visual signature, your introduction, and an essential element of your journey as a musician. Make it count! 🎶🖼️

The three most important reasons for training with a shot timer at the shooting range are:

Realistic Simulation: Shot timers create time pressure, simulating real-world shooting scenarios and helping individuals practice under time constraints.

Stress Inoculation: Shot timers induce controlled stress, allowing shooters to develop the ability to stay calm and make accurate shots under pressure, which is crucial for self-defense and competition.

Identifies Weaknesses and Tracks Progress: Shot timers provide data that helps shooters identify areas for improvement, set goals, and track their progress over time, leading to more efficient and effective training.

The importance of vulnerability in music can be summarized in several key points:

Emotional Connection: Vulnerability fosters a deep emotional bond between artists and listeners.

Authenticity: It contributes to the authenticity of music by allowing artists to express genuine emotions and experiences.

Catharsis: Vulnerability provides a therapeutic outlet, allowing artists to process and convey complex emotions.

Artistic Growth: It serves as a catalyst for artistic growth, encouraging experimentation and creative exploration.

Empowerment: Vulnerability in music can empower both artists and listeners by sharing stories of overcoming challenges.

Timelessness: Authentically vulnerable music tends to have a timeless quality, resonating across generations.

Diverse Perspectives: Embracing vulnerability allows for a diverse range of perspectives and narratives in music.

While other aspects of cover art, such as storytelling and alignment with the music’s theme, are important, they often serve to reinforce the primary goal of capturing the audience’s attention. Without this initial engagement, the cover art may not fulfill its other functions effectively. Therefore, the ability to grab the audience’s attention is arguably the most critical aspect of good cover art for a rap artist.

FREE GAME 👉🏽 A well-defined brand establishes a connection with your audience, making your music more memorable and distinguishable. It can also attract collaborations, sponsorships, and opportunities, contributing to long-term success in the music industry. 

1. **Define Your Identity:** Clearly articulate what makes you unique as an artist. Identify your musical style, values, and the emotions you want to convey through your work. This clarity forms the foundation for your brand.

2. **Consistent Visuals and Messaging:** Maintain a cohesive visual presence across platforms, including album covers, social media, and promotional materials. Consistency in visuals and messaging helps reinforce your brand identity and makes it easily recognizable to your audience.

3. **Engage with Your Audience:** Actively interact with your fans through social media, live performances, and other platforms. Building a community fosters a personal connection with your audience, enhancing their loyalty to your brand. Responding to comments, sharing behind-the-scenes glimpses, and involving your audience in your journey can make a significant impact.
